title.narrative: Feed the Future Malawi Agriculture Diversification (AgDiv)

description.narrative: (Malawi): USAID's Agriculture Diversification (AgDiv) activity promotes agricultural production, nutrition, resilience, and economic growth by helping farmers diversify away from maize into more profitable and nutritious crops, including legumes and orange-fleshed sweet potato. AgDiv will provide technical assistance, training, new technologies, demonstration plots, and media campaigns to support farmer adoption of improved technologies and practices and to improve partnerships among farmers, buyers, input suppliers, and financiers. AgDiv will use FY 2020 funds to: (1) build resilience through watershed management, reduce deforestation, and increase adoption of drip irrigation; (2) increase access to markets and finance; (3) strengthen capacity of private enterprises; (4) stimulate entrepreneurship; (5) increase productivity of legumes and orange-fleshed sweet potatoes; (6) promote good nutrition and gender related behavior change such as women empowerment; (7) and enhance resilience to shocks. .Diversification away from low-value, low-nutrient maize into legumes and orange-fleshed sweet potato will help farmers improve their dietary diversity, increase their incomes, and boost their resilience, thereby contributing to reductions in rural stunting and poverty. AgDiv partners with the private sector to implement many of its interventions, strengthening links along value chains and ensuring sustainability. .Reducing poverty, improving nutrition, and enhancing resilience to shocks are vital to achieving the Malawi Integrated Country Strategy Mission Objective 1.2 - Increase sustainable livelihoods. Increased resilience to shocks will also reduce Malawi's chronic dependence on humanitarian assistance. Further, this activity will help Malawi achieve its National Security Strategy objectives of supporting growth by unlocking the economic potential of citizens, advancing private sector interests, mobilizing private sector resources, and capitalizing on new technologies...
